In the papers, "Newly reported  cases in the last year" become "new cases which happened last year". "Women and girls" becomes "girls". "Recorded on women and girls in the UK" becomes "Undertaken on girls in the UK".

The tabloid narrative is of thousands of immigrants in the UK abusing their children. That's not visible in the data. The truth is that there is a historic and persistent practice abroad.

@SamWhyte Absolutely! The UK Association of Professional Piercers did amazing outreach work with women in the UK who had been victims abroad, who themselves were rightly so angry that the narrative was about huge numbers of immigrant mothers in the UK abusing their children!
So if we're really worried about FGM (we should be), we should see the "What about the poor, immigrant babies?" line as the emotional obfuscation it is.
NHS data consistently shows that nearly 100% of dr-reported FGM in the UK and on UK born women and girls was undertaken on adults, and is in the category which includes genital piercing.

In one case, a girl with "irregular genitals" was claimed to be a victim by an unqualified activist; in another, a dr, treating a woman from Somalia who had been an FGM victim, giving birth in the UK, was prosecuted for stitching a vaginal tear during childbirth as an emergency.
FGM is an awful scourge and must be eliminated, but almost no-one using it as a rhetorical cudgel is in the slight bit interested in the details and the harms misguided activism does.

Don't get me wrong, I want and work hard to ensure that students attend lectures. But I simply don't believe that students whose staff are being forced to teach them will get a better education than students who are told, clearly, what lectures are, and what they're for.

If students were really so insistent about the necessity of lectures to their learning, attendance would be much better than it is. No student thinks missing a lecture is a bad thing, generally speaking.

Many students come to university thinking, as at A-Level that their task is to recall everything their lecturers say in class, full stop. No. Lectures are introductions to topics. Students (in humanities at least) should be doing independent learning!
Why are we hardening the idea that a lecture is the sum total of learning provision at a university, rather than a useful but neither necessary nor sufficient component of it?

Lectures are not so important they cannot be missed, nor so singular that their content cannot be learned by students independently, in the library. Students miss lectures *all the time*. 

Where did this idea come from that students demand lectures to be "Satisfied"?

Carr, by contrast, on stage and off (and in the run up to that joke) pitches himself as saying what everyone is thinking but is too scared of cancel culture to actually say.

There's lots of reasonable criticism of Silverman, and her blindspots, and where that show maybe went too far. But there's a solid theory of comedy behind it which sets it up as commentary on evil not celebration of evil.

But the targets of her jokes -- even the ones about genocide and rape -- are always prevailing social attitudes, and she deliberately sets up her character at the very beginning of the set (and in the DVD skits) to make that as clear as possible.

That's what is so grotesque about it. It's not because it's "offensive", it's because the necessary chain of logic that, purportedly, turns this from offense into "comedy". Who, exactly, are we laughing at here? Why? To what end? To what affect?

Where, in other words, is the joke? Carr probably doesn't think about his 'jokes' in this way, at least not overtly. But he must have a sense of what separates a joke from plain hate. So, how would he defend this? Why, basically, is this funny?

Outrage comics like Carr, in particular, need a theory of comedy. They're not just getting up and saying offensive things. He didn't stand up and directly say "It's good that Roma and Sinti people were massacred". So the question becomes: "Why is this funny, not just offensive?".
